<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54148i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54148i">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54148i"> 148(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Je double caps / find bear (prays) <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54148i"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Du point de vue linguistique, dit-il, la formule n&apos;a pas toujours la forme d&apos;une <mark>pri&egrave;re</mark>. Il en est beaucoup o&ugrave; le verbe n&apos;est pas &agrave; l&apos;optatif, ni &agrave; l&apos;imp&eacute;ratif, mais &agrave; l&apos;indicatif. Mais l&apos;&eacute;nonciation du fait lui-m&ecirc;me est une paraphrase du souhait qui se produit; en r&eacute;alit&eacute;, le sens de la formule est optatif. Lorsque le chasseur, dans son kayak, murmure ou r&eacute;cite: <mark>&laquo;Je double le cap, &laquo;que me donnera-t-il? Il me donnera un ours&raquo;</mark>, ce qu&apos;il a dans l&apos;esprit est: &laquo;Je souhaite que, lorsque j&apos;aurai doubl&eacute; ce cap, je puisse voir (c&apos;est-&agrave;-dire tuer) &laquo;un ours.&raquo; <br><font color="green">["From a linguistic point of view," he says, "the formula is not always in the form of a prayer. There are many where the verb is not optional, not imperative, but indicative. But the statement of the fact itself is a paraphrase of the wish that occurs; in reality, the meaning of the formula is optional. When the hunter, in his kayak, whispers or recites: "I double the course," what will he give me? He will give me a bear", what he has in mind is: "I wish that, when I have doubled this course, I will be able to see (that is to say kill)" a bear.]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 285</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
